<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Fee structures</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic way that investment bankers =
get paid for sell-side merger advice=C2=A0is that they get a percentage of =
the deal value. If you sell your company for $10 billion, the bankers get $=
50 million, 0.5% of the deal value, something like that. If you sell it for=
 $9 billion, they get $45 million. This gives the bankers an incentive to g=
et a higher price, which is what you want. (This is sometimes also the fee =
structure for=C2=A0<em>buy-</em>side bankers, which gives=C2=A0<em>them=C2=
=A0</em>an incentive to push for a higher price, which is weird!)</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand it mostly gives the bankers an inc=
entive to get a deal done. Selling a company for $7 billion and getting a $=
35 million fee is vastly preferable to insisting on a $12 billion valuation=
, losing the deal, and getting nothing. Whereas for the company and its sha=
reholders, remaining independent can=C2=A0be much better than accepting a d=
eal for too little money. So there is a conflict of interest. The company w=
ill get some interest from=C2=A0a buyer, it will hire bankers, the buyer wi=
ll come in with a low offer, the company will say =E2=80=9Cmeh never mind w=
e=E2=80=99re fine,=E2=80=9D and the bankers will say =E2=80=9Cwell wait a m=
inute are you sure you=E2=80=99re fine=E2=80=9D and push to get a deal done=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to manage this conflict =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0besides just ignoring the bankers! totally a thing you can do =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0is to modify the bankers=E2=80=99 fee structure. For instance:</p>=
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If the company sells for less than $1=
0 billion, the bankers get nothing.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">If the company sells for more than $10 billion, the bankers get 5% of the=
 amount over $10 billion.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If the c=
ompany doesn=E2=80=99t sell now, the bankers get the first shot at selling =
it later.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That way the bankers have n=
o incentive to take a bad deal. Arguably this goes too far =E2=80=94=C2=A0i=
f $9 billion is the best the company is going to do, someone should tell th=
em that! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s a choice you could make. Instead o=
f incentivizing the bankers to be conservative and take any deal they can g=
et, you incentivize them to be super-aggressive and hold out for the best p=
ossible deal.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One implication of that fee s=
tructure is that if the banker does a really good job he gets a really big =
check. Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/25959463.279651/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy90aGlzLWJhbmtlci1=
pcy1taW50aW5nLW1vbmV5LWluLXRoZS1maW50ZWNoLWJvb20tMTE2Mzg3MTI4MDE_c3Q9azFyZX=
YxNWJ3N2x3OW9hJnJlZmxpbms9YXJ0aWNsZV9jb3B5VVJMX3NoYXJl/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB63b44c41" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">a Wall Street Journal story</a> about Steve McLaughl=
in of fintech banking boutique Financial Technology Partners LP:</p><blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An early deal that put the firm on the ma=
p was for Lynk Systems Inc., a credit-card processor. According to Mr. McLa=
ughlin, the company had previously hired Merrill Lynch to find a buyer and =
fetched an offer of around $150 million. He promised to beat it. In return,=
 Lynk offered him 5% of any deal price over $300 million. Mr. McLaughlin al=
l but moved into a hotel near Lynk=E2=80=99s headquarters in Atlanta. In 20=
04, the company was sold to Royal Bank of Scotland for $525 million.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That became Mr. McLaughlin=E2=80=99s blueprint: F=
ind companies that are opaquely valued or misunderstood. Negotiate unusual =
fee structures. And only represent sellers, never investors or potential ac=
quirers. It is a lesson Mr. McLaughlin said he learned from his mom, a Real=
tor. =E2=80=9CAlways get the listing,=E2=80=9D he said.=C2=A0</p></blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also there is some venture investing but fo=
r banking fees:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some of FT Part=
ners=E2=80=99 biggest wins took more than a decade. When AvidXchange approa=
ched Mr. McLaughlin in 2009 for help raising $5 million, he said it wasn=E2=
=80=99t worth the time. He changed his mind when the company agreed to sign=
 an engagement letter that guaranteed FT Partners a role on any deal the co=
mpany did for the next 50 years. He also joined AvidXchange=E2=80=99s board=
 of directors.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AvidXchange went from a few =
million dollars in annual revenue in 2009 to $186 million in 2020. An Octob=
er IPO valued the commercial-payments company at about $5 billion. On top o=
f the stake Mr. McLaughlin owns in the company, FT Partners collected a rou=
ghly 6% fee on the $1 billion it helped AvidXchange raise over nearly a doz=
en years.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mike Praeger, AvidXchange=E2=80=
=99s chief executive, said Mr. McLaughlin did plenty of work for the compan=
y outside of fundraisings, including late-night phone calls and weekend fli=
ghts to North Carolina to map out strategy. He also said Mr. McLaughlin tal=
ked him out of selling the company at prices well below its current market =
value.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically if you have a=
 contract saying that (1) you will advise on any deal the company does for =
50 years and (2) you=E2=80=99ll get 6% of the proceeds, then you, uh, own 6=
% of the company? Which might make you a better long-term advisor, more ali=
gned with shareholders and better able to maximize value, than if you just =
got paid a one-time transactional fee. Also if you pick the right company t=
o do this deal with it can make you pretty rich.</p><table class=3D"liveint=
ent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"cent=
er">
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"2">
